-- Oil Options Volatility Rises as Futures Decline for Third Day
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-13T20:14:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-13/oil-options-volatility-rises-as-futures-decline-for-third-day.html
Crude oil options volatility rose as
the underlying futures declined for a third straight session.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 21.24 percent at 3:55 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , up from 20.41 p.m. on May 10.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery dropped 87
cents, or 0.9 percent, to settle at $95.17 a barrel a barrel on
the Nymex. July-delivery WTI fell 88 cents to $95.41.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
June $90 puts, which slid 1 cent to 6 cents a barrel on volume
of 2,650 contracts at 3:56 p.m. in  New York . June $94 puts were
the second-most active, advancing 14 cents to 49 cents a barrel
on 2,385 lots.  Calls accounted for 51 percent of electronic trading volume
today. Puts made up 57 percent of the prior trading dayâ€™s volume
of 178,913 contracts.  June $90 puts were the most-active options traded in the
previous session, with 18,044 contracts changing hands. They
rose 1 cent to 7 cents a barrel. June $88 puts increased 1 cent
to 4 cents a barrel on 7,964 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $80 puts with 37,681
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 37,387 lots and
December $110 calls with 34,263.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
